{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:29:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:29:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12413"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12413"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.59,0.18,0.03,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111153"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4921"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93277"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1827"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35881"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111153"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with a painful, swollen left arm. Three days ago she was playing with her cat when it bit her on the forearm. She has no other health issues and is not on any medications. On examination her blood pressure is 110/90 mmHg, pulse 98/min and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. Her left arm is reddened and swollen, with an area of induration around the bite mark in the mid forearm. Two puncture marks are visible.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical mupirocin ointment","Intravenous amoxicillin+clavulanate","Oral cephalexin","Oral diclofenac combined with local heat therapy","Intravenous ceftriaxone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with a deep infection after a cat bite. Even if this patient had attended soon after the bite had occurred, the puncture marks alone would be indicative of infection treatment with an antibiotic would have been indicated. Cat bites should always be considered a high risk for infection as more often than not they cause deep puncture wounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the infection is obvious and the best treatment option would be the administration of an intravenous antibiotic such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous amoxicillin and clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E. This treatment regimen is recommended by ETG in Australia specifically for the treatment of cat bites, the intravenous route of administration allows for systemic exposure of the drug in adequate concentration to effectively treat the underlying infection along with added benefits like rapid exposure to the site of the infection and reduction in the risk of complications and improvement in the chances of a successful outcome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe use of topical ointment like \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical mupirocin ointment\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for treating deep tissue infections like the one in the scenario. The cutaneous administration of antibiotics has limited distribution and would not result in adequate systemic concentrations of the drug to effectively treat the deep tissue infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral cephalexin\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly used to treat skin and soft tissue infections but it may not provide sufficient coverage for the potential bacterial pathogens involved in a cat bite which are shown to be resistant to cephalexin in some cases. Therefore, intravenous antibiotics with broader spectrum coverage, such as amoxicillin-clavulanate, would be more appropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral diclofenac combined with local heat therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may provide the patient with a soothing effect and can temporarily relieve pain, but this will not address the underlying problem, which is a potentially deep tissue infection following a cat bite. This treatment will only be symptomatic and may lead to further complications due to the underlying infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone \u003C/strong\u003Eis usually a good treatment option for deep tissue infections, but it is not the treatment option recommended for cat bites in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous amoxicillin plus clavulanate is the treatment of choice for treating cat bites.","Antibiotics should always be considered for cat bites as they will often lead to a deep puncture wound."],"references":["Broom J, Woods ML. Management of bite injuries. Aust Prescr [Internet]. 2006 Mar 3 [cited 2025 Aug 9];29(6):6\u20138. Available from: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/management-of-bite-injuries.html","Hurt JB, Maday KR. Management and treatment of animal bites. JAAPA. 2018 Apr;31(4):27-31. doi: 10.1097/01.JAA.0000531049.59137.cd. PMID: 30973531. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30973531/","Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Animal and human bites [Internet]. Melbourne: The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital; [cited 2025 Aug 9]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Animal_and_human_bites/","Colmers-Gray IN, Tulloch JS, Dostaler G, Bai AD. Management of mammalian bites. BMJ. 2023 Feb 2;380:e071921. doi: 10.1136/bmj-2022-071921. PMID: 36731914. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36731914/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93277"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12413"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93277"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T19:09:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T19:10:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4921"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111153"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attrib